The paper deals with algorithms for finding Nash equilibria in games, which is a topic in game theory (cs.GT). The use of sparse payoff matrices and the PPAD-completeness of exact solutions suggest a connection to computational complexity (cs.CC). The construction of a sparse eps-cover and the use of probability distributions suggest a connection to probability and statistics (cs.IT). The use of PTAS and the development of lower bounds suggest a connection to approximation algorithms (cs.APPROX). Finally, the use of algorithms and computational methods suggests a connection to artificial intelligence (cs.AI).
